div.div:
An example of how applying "differences to relevant subsets" is useful to solve problems.
Applying differences like opposites to a structure's variables is useful in a case such as where one of those variables is an error (a negative or costly or useless structure) bc of its proximity to a problem (addiction) and its function to change position closer to that problem, causing the problem.
The 'addictiveness' variable doesn't need to be changed, even though it's part of the problem, if another part of the problem, such as the negative side effects, can be changed instead. So either of these variables is possible to differentiate to solve the problem. "Find a drug with fewer negative side effects (other than addictiveness, which is one of them but can be isolated in a useful way)" is the useful intent to fulfill, to solve the problem specifically (implement the solution).
That intent is possible because the reason for the 'addictiveness' is that the bio system interprets associated addictive substances as useful in some way, because sometimes they are, which means there is variation in the set of all addictive substances, enough variation to have opposites in it, in the variable of side effects and specifically in the variable of addictiveness as well, such as with vitamins.
The person can become more addicted but still not have a problem in the positive example, which is an abstract structure that is automatically identifiable by "applying differences to relevant subsets (relevant such as alternate)", similar to how removing the other error variable of 'addictiveness' reduces the impact/meaning of the negative side effects to a trivial variable.
